  "prompt": "What is the difference between clause and provision?",
  "response": "The terms \"clause\" and \"provision\" are often used in legal and contractual contexts, and though they can sometimes be used interchangeably, they usually have distinct meanings:\n\n1. **Clause**:\n   - A clause is a specific segment or section of a legal document, contract, or agreement. It usually addresses a particular point or aspect of the contract, such as the terms of payment, responsibilities of the parties, or conditions for termination.\n   - Clauses are typically numbered or labeled to organize the document and make it easier to reference specific parts.\n   - Clauses can be very specific and detailed, sometimes encompassing several paragraphs, addressing a single issue or topic.\n\n2. **Provision**:\n   - A provision refers more generally to any condition or requirement found within a contract or legal document. It is a term used to describe rules or stipulations that have been provided for or included within the document.\n   - Provisions may be contained within a clause; in fact, a clause can encompass several provisions. In this sense, a provision is more about the substance of what is being agreed to, rather than how it is organized within the document.\n   - Provisions can relate to a wide range of aspects of the agreement, including timelines, obligations, rights, and remedies.\n\nIn summary, while every clause contains one or more provisions, not every provision is a standalone clause. Clauses are structural components of documents, while provisions cover the substantive terms and conditions agreed upon by the parties involved.",
